gomodel:SYNGO_1187  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Kennedy et al aim to provide experimental evidence for exocytosis at dendritic postsynaptic membranes. The authors take advantage of a two-color reporters by fusing transferrin receptor and/or GluA1 to mCherry and SEP-tag (PHluorin variant) in order to monitor trafficking of RE. Furthermore, the authors demonstrate by shRNA and expression of dominant negative soluble version of stx4 that the protein is required for exocytosis of RE. Both approaches reduce transferrin cycling to the PM in response to stimulation (glycine/bicuculline).\nKennedy et al aim to validate their findings by a controversial method of whole IgG-mediated cross-linking of exogenously HA-tagged syntaxin-4 prior to stimulation and observe reduced exocytosis (by means of fluorescent detection of RE cargo translocation to the membrane).\nAlthough these results only indirectly suggest involvement of Q SNARE molecule syntaxin 4 in postsynaptic RE exocytosis, they remain controversial (see Jurado et al 2013, Neuron and additional literature).. Experimental description: - \"Hippocampal neuron cultures were prepared from E18 rat embryos and grown on 18 mm poly-D-lysine coated coverslips as previously described (Ehlers, 2000). \"\n\nGeneration of Recombinant Stx3ΔTM and Stx4ΔTM\nRecombinant Stx4ΔTM and Stx3ΔTM were generated as N-terminal GST fusion proteins by cloning sequences corresponding to amino acids 2-273 of human Stx4 and amino acids 2-262 of Stx3 into pGEX-6P-3 (Amersham Biosciences).\n\nExtended Experimental Procedures\nConstructs\nTfR-SEP was previously described (Park et al., 2006). Human Stx4 and Stx3 clones were provided by Dr. Thomas Weimbs (University of California, Santa Barbara)" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1542-3498" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0808-7003" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-3898-5197" ;
        dc:date           "2018-03-12" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_1187" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

